column5: Diversity & Creating Equity Project: This covers payments to our DEI consultants Dr Sharon Washington (who is phasing out) and  On The Margins (our new consultant) for our ongoing work around DEI in the program.  You will see that we have divided the total amount paid to our consultants across multiple grants.  Both SWC and On The Margins create workshops centered on power hierarchies, inclusive team-building exercises, leadership consultation, 1:1 coaching for faculty, office hours for residents and assists us in interpretation and presentation of our Annual DEI Climate Survey results. </Description>

column4: <Description>Wellness activities  The wellness committee organizes and executes a number of events throughout the year to support residents and faculty.  The majority of these expenses go to the purchasing and delivery of healthy food to inpatient teams during difficult times of the year such as winter or as we transition from one academic year to the next or when we have times when fewer residents are covering the hospital services while other residents are offsite doing connecting and wellness activities such as walks, resiliency training, and community activities.  We purchase supplies such as journals, water bottles for residents to use during wellness weeks.  We have practitioners such as yoga instructors teach during wellness focused weeks.  We also have a wellness evening activity once a year where we use the money to sponsor food at the food truck court to promote resident connection and relationship building.</Description>

<Description>We plan to use these funds to continue our community engagement/pipeline efforts, our DEI invited speaker/author program, and get our clinic patient advocate program started to assist with the large case management and secretarial burden experienced by our residents in their continuity clinic. To support a Social Justice/Wellness book club where we discuss social justice books such as Medical Apartheid by Harriet Washington, Minor Feelings by Cathy Park Hong, Daring Greatly by Brene Brown, and Compassionomics by Trzeciak and Mazzarelli. We have also held monthly Wellness debriefs to help residents deal with the many deaths and isolation during the COVID epidemic. We have also continued a monthly evening meeting with discussion of a combined IM and Peds topic. The feedback for these efforts is very positive but nevertheless we have found that attendance rises by 2-3 fold when food is provided. For use in our High School Clinic (the Ribbon Cutting Ceremony was 8/18/23), and Adolescent Care and Transition Clinic to help educate residents and  provide them valuable education in these critical and exciting primary care delivery settings. To purchase supplies such as basic first aid/wound care materials, socks, gloves, masks, wipes, hand sanitizer, some basic medications, condoms, dental dams, portable pulse ox/HR monitors. temperature probe, weight scale, glucometers, as well as toys or books for the nurses to give the children after they receive their vaccines. Board study educational materials for Medicine and Pediatrics. For use in purchasing SNMA, LMSA, ACP, and AAP memberships for residents and faculty. Travel, hotel, and conference fees for residents to attend academic conferences and URM recruitment conferences. Our clinics currently attract a high level of complex patients particularly adults with pediatric disease, as a result our case manager manages more than twice the number of complex patients requiring things such as durable medical equipment as their counterpart in other clinics. To hire patient advocates and medical scribes to reduce the large case management and secretarial burden on residents and faculty in complex patient primary and transitional care and allow them to focus more on clinical education and patient care. With the goal of attracting more residents and retaining our faculty in primary care. To pay for flight, hotel, and speaker fee to invite teachers/authors such as Harriett Washington, Richard Garcia, Gregory Boyle, Nikole Hannah-Jones, William McDade, and Mariame Kaba ranging from topics in Medicine to topics in Social Justice and the many valuable topics in between, to enhance our understanding of areas critical to graduate medical education in combined internal medicine such as social justice, transitional care, race in medicine, compassion, and others. A third of our residents identify as URM and all are selected for their sincere interest in serving disadvantaged communities. By supporting community engagement, advocacy and pipeline experiences that will enhance our efforts to recruit these applicants and boost their interest in primary care with employment of community member and high school level health advocates, educational materials, supplies, food, or other materials during events such as Grand Rounds for local high school or middle school students, discussing parenting and questions for the pediatrician with ex-gang members at Homeboy Industries, and health discussions with local students and community members.</Description>
